# Java Secure Coding

## Input Validation
- Validate all external input at system boundaries (controllers, message handlers, file readers)
- Use Bean Validation (`@NotNull`, `@Size`, `@Pattern`) for declarative validation
- Reject invalid input early -- fail fast
- Sanitize output to prevent XSS when rendering user-supplied content

## Injection Prevention
- SQL: always use parameterized queries or Spring Data query methods -- never string concatenation
- LDAP, XPath, OS commands: use parameterized APIs
- Log injection: sanitize user input before logging (strip newlines, control characters)
- Deserialization: never deserialize untrusted data with Java serialization; use JSON/XML with strict schemas

## Secrets Management
- Never hardcode secrets (passwords, API keys, tokens) in source code
- Use environment variables, vault services, or Spring Cloud Config for secrets
- Exclude secret files from version control (`.env`, `credentials.json` in `.gitignore`)
- Rotate secrets regularly; support hot-reloading where possible

## Authentication and Authorization
- Use Spring Security `SecurityFilterChain` for HTTP security
- Enforce authentication on all endpoints by default; explicitly permit public endpoints
- Use method-level security (`@PreAuthorize`, `@Secured`) for fine-grained access control
- Store passwords with bcrypt or Argon2 -- never MD5 or SHA-1

## Cryptography
- Use `java.security` and `javax.crypto` APIs -- never custom crypto
- TLS 1.2+ for all network communication
- Secure random: `SecureRandom`, never `Random` for security-sensitive contexts
- Key sizes: RSA >= 2048, AES >= 256, ECDSA >= P-256

## Dependency Security
- Scan dependencies with OWASP Dependency-Check in every build
- Subscribe to security advisories for direct dependencies
- Pin dependency versions; review changelogs before upgrading
- Remove unused dependencies to reduce attack surface

## Secure Defaults
- HttpOnly, Secure, SameSite flags on cookies
- CSRF protection enabled by default (disable only for stateless APIs with token auth)
- CORS configured explicitly per endpoint -- never `allowedOrigins("*")` in production
- Response headers: `X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff`, `X-Frame-Options: DENY`

## Error Handling for Security
- Never expose stack traces, class names, or internal paths in API error responses
- Use Problem Details (RFC 9457) with generic error messages
- Log detailed errors server-side with correlation IDs

